<!-- Section 5: Common Failures -->
<section id="common-failures" class="mb-16">
<h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">5. Common Certification Failures</h2>
<p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">Understanding why chargers fail safety testing helps avoid costly redesigns. Approximately 40% of first-time submissions from new manufacturers fail at least one critical test.</p>

<div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
<div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 rounded-r-xl p-6">
<h3 class="font-black text-red-700 uppercase mb-2">1. Fire Enclosure Failures</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-3">The charger casing catches fire during fault condition testing. Common causes: insufficient flame-retardant materials, inadequate ventilation, or recycled plastics.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 text-xs"><strong>Solution:</strong> Specify V-0 rated UL94 materials that pass 850&deg;C glow wire testing.</p>
</div>
<div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 rounded-r-xl p-6">
<h3 class="font-black text-red-700 uppercase mb-2">2. Temperature Limit Exceedance</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-3">Accessible surfaces exceed 77&deg;C during normal operation, creating burn hazards.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 text-xs"><strong>Solution:</strong> Thermal pads, adequate heat sinks, OTP shutdown at 105&deg;C.</p>
</div>
<div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 rounded-r-xl p-6">
<h3 class="font-black text-red-700 uppercase mb-2">3. Dielectric Strength Breakdown</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-3">Insulation fails under 1500V AC testing. Current leaks create shock hazards.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 text-xs"><strong>Solution:</strong> Maintain minimum 4mm creepage distances, use triple-insulated transformer wire.</p>
</div>
<div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 rounded-r-xl p-6">
<h3 class="font-black text-red-700 uppercase mb-2">4. Single Fault Conditions</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-3">When components fail, the charger creates hazards instead of safely shutting down.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 text-xs"><strong>Solution:</strong> Redundant protection circuits. Every safety function needs a backup.</p>
</div>
<div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 rounded-r-xl p-6">
<h3 class="font-black text-red-700 uppercase mb-2">5. Mechanical Strength Issues</h3>
<p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-3">Cracked housings, loose USB ports, or detached AC prongs under stress testing.</p>
<p class="text-slate-600 text-xs"><strong>Solution:</strong> Ultrasonically welded seams, thermal glue for internal components.</p>
</div>
</div>
</section>

